description: {"blocks":[{"key":"3ahs0","text":"Research on microplastic pollution and its effects on atmospheric, aquatic, and terrestrial environments has grown rapidly as potential risks for human health are recognized. Recently, microplastic particles have been detected in a variety of human tissue samples (e.g., blood, placenta, lung tissue), but studies use different methods of collection, preparation, and analysis, making results difficult to compare. In particular, the risk of microplastic contamination during sample collection is high and can potentially produce misleading results. Here we present a set of guidelines to mitigate all sources of potential plastic contamination while collecting cadaveric tissue samples. We discuss specific protocols for the collection of three tissue types: (1) internal body fluids; (2) soft tissue; and (3) tissue lining body orifices. Guidelines for each tissue type include sterilization of equipment and specimen, extraction of the sample, and containment of the cadaveric specimen after removal. Each methodology has the potential to be modified to collect samples from any anatomical region within the human body. Representatives from each tissue type (intestinal contents, lung tissue, and contents from the nasal cavity) are presented.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"cp6ff","text":"Place the tools in a laminar flow hood or clean bench to dry.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cb7h5","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"6ki8u","text":"an","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"notes","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"8hugd","text":"To further protect the tools and dissection tray from particulates within the hood, place tools on top of aluminum foil within the hood, covering them with an upside-down dissection tray. {"blocks":[{"key":"e5uii","text":"Once all tools are dry, place them in the dissection tray(s) and cover the tray(s) with aluminum foil until needed.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fli0b","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"1vu7m","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"notes","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"c3c41","text":"Be sure there are no tears or damage to the aluminum covering that will reduce its shielding function.","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Internal body fluids (representative body region: intestinal contents)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"fmef2","text":"Using a scalpel (size 10 blade), make a 7.5 cm vertical incision from the umbilicus running toward the xiphoid process. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a4det","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"4thpr","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"notes","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"55tib","text":"Be sure to only cut through the skin, adipose, and musculature. If you cannot visually see the depth of the incision, use your fingertips to feel that you have cut through the musculature but have not cut into the greater omentum covering the abdominal viscera or the abdominal viscera itself.","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Internal body fluids (representative body region: intestinal contents)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"cjb0b","text":"Using forceps and your fingers, locate the preferred section of the intestine and pull it out of the abdominal cavity without additional incisions, leaving any other viscera in place.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cu3tg","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"bulfc","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"notes","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"em1oa","text":"A small pair of scissors can be used to cut through peritoneal structures that might be covering the intestine (e.g., greater omentum, posterior rectus sheath).","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Internal body fluids (representative body region: intestinal contents)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"6le9u","text":"After the desired segment of the intestine is removed from the abdominal cavity, use the linear stapler to secure contents within the intestine. Staple 2 sites, 3 cm from each other, on both the proximal and distal ends of the intestinal segment.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Internal body fluids (representative body region: intestinal contents)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"et227","text":"Use scalpel to cut between the staple sites on both ends.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Internal body fluids (representative body region: intestinal contents)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"a6u87","text":"Remove the segment of intestine so that contents can later be removed and analyzed.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Soft tissue (representative body region: lung tissue)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"cbcvi","text":"Using a scalpel (10 blade), make a 5 cm incision in the intercostal space, cutting through skin and musculature.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9msj4","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"fh0km","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"notes","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[{"length":2,"offset":81,"style":"sup"},{"length":2,"offset":89,"style":"sup"},{"length":2,"offset":96,"style":"sup"},{"length":2,"offset":104,"style":"sup"}],"key":"c0k5p","text":"When possible, the body should be in a supine position. An incision between the 3rd and 4th or 4th and 5th rib on the superior aspect of the thoracic cage will often give more space to maneuver the tools and will also provide better, more visible access to the lung tissue.","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Soft tissue (representative body region: lung tissue)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"f5bo8","text":"Using your fingers, locate the lung tissue. Insert forceps or a hemostat into the incision, using the tool to grab and stabilize the lung segment.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Soft tissue (representative body region: lung tissue)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"1382r","text":"Still holding the lung segment, push the biopsy punch through the tissue.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cjctf","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"5iq26","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"notes","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"3sdj5","text":"If the biopsy punch does not transect the tissue segment, angle the punch in a superior direction while turning it 360 degrees, breaking the tissue within the biopsy punch free from the intact lung.","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Soft tissue (representative body region: lung tissue)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"dr9at","text":"Remove the biopsy punch from the thoracic cavity and use forceps or a probe to push tissue through the biopsy punch and into a glass container.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Soft tissue (representative body region: lung tissue)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"5bjre","text":"Repeat until you have collected the desired amount of tissue.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Tissues lining body orifices (representative body region: nasal cavity)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"86kvp","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"30ug5","text":"Insert the scalpel blade into one or both nostrils and gently scrape the lateral and medial walls, removing portions of the mucosal membrane.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Tissues lining body orifices (representative body region: nasal cavity)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"77b1q","text":"Insert glass collection jar into nares.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7ebvr","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"b62sj","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"notes","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"co9qn","text":"If the nostril diameter is larger than the glass collection jar, pinch the surrounding skin to seal the space.","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Tissues lining body orifices (representative body region: nasal cavity)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"cspj0","text":"Use a 16-gauge syringe needle to pierce the lateral nostril wall just superior to the inferior edge.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Extraction of Tissue: Tissues lining body orifices (representative body region: nasal cavity)
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"45rq0","text":"Using a new needle, draw particle-free water into a glass syringe and insert the needle into the nostril through the piercing. With the needle pointing in a superior direction, flush the nasal cavity. Allow the particle-free water and nasal contents to flow into the glass collection jar.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d760u","text":"Seal the glass containment jar(s) with metal lid(s), aluminum foil, or glass lid(s).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"g667","text":"Human tissues should be frozen at -20 ̊ C until they are ready for analysis preparation. Leave additional space at the top of the collection jar to account for the expansion of water within the tissue.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2fdnd","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"9r896","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4r0iq","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"notes","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"cmuro","text":"If tissues are to be stored in other liquids (e.g., formalin, formaldehyde) after extraction, be sure that these liquids are also filtered and added as a component of the blanks to later be analyzed for contamination.","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

warning: {"blocks":[{"key":"894sh","text":"Safety warnings","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":15}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f0pit","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2c3fg","text":"Working with cadavers can pose the risk of exposure to infectious disease. Cadavers should be screened for the following infectious pathogens prior to any sample collection: Tuberculosis, hepatitis B and C, AIDS and HIV, MRSA, VRSA, or VRE, SARS-CoV-2, meningitis, septicemia, and prions that cause transmissible spongiform encephalopathies such as Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD). ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ef7ch","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cade5","text":"Proper protective clothing, gloves, and good hygiene measures can reduce the risks of working with a cadaveric specimen to a minimum.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8etvq","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ebj7s","text":"Scalpel blades are sharp, thin, and can easily be broken. Lacerations from a scalpel blade can cause serious injury and increase the exposure risk to blood borne pathogens. Never try to insert, adjust, or remove a scalpel blade with your hands. Properly dispose of blades in a sharps container immediately after use.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
